Note:
Protocol Buffers Lexer - Proto3/Proto2 compliant tokenization

This file provides lexical analysis for Protocol Buffers (.proto) files
supporting both proto2 and proto3 syntax.

Protocol Buffers Structure:
- Syntax declaration: syntax = "proto3";
- Package declarations: package com.example;
- Import statements: import "other.proto";
- Message definitions with typed fields
- Enum definitions
- Service definitions (gRPC)
- Options and annotations
- Comments (// and /* */)

Token Types:
- Keywords (syntax, package, import, message, enum, service, rpc, etc.)
- Types (int32, string, bool, etc.)
- Identifiers (message names, field names)
- Literals (strings, numbers)
- Operators and delimiters
- Comments

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0

Note: Keywords
Constant TOKEN_SYNTAX as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_PACKAGE as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_IMPORT as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_MESSAGE as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_ENUM as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_SERVICE as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_RPC as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_RETURNS as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_OPTION as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_REPEATED as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_OPTIONAL as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_REQUIRED as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_RESERVED as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_ONEOF as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_MAP as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_STREAM as Integer is 16

Note: Literals and identifiers
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER_LITERAL as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_BOOLEAN_LITERAL as Integer is 23

Note: Operators and delimiters
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 30
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 31
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE as Integer is 32
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE as Integer is 33
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN as Integer is 34
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN as Integer is 35
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET as Integer is 36
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET as Integer is 37
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_ANGLE as Integer is 38
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_ANGLE as Integer is 39
Constant TOKEN_DOT as Integer is 40
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 41
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 42

Note: Comments
Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 50

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Five-field token record: type tag, pointer/length slice into source for
lexeme content (non-owning), and 1-based diagnostic line/column. The
slice form avoids per-token heap allocation for identifiers and numbers
since proto files rarely contain string content that requires
transformation.
@End Reasoning
Type called "Token":
    type as Integer           Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer         Note: Pointer to token text
    lexeme_length as Integer  Note: Length of token text
    line as Integer           Note: Line number
    column as Integer         Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Five-field lexer state: source pointer/length (length cached so peek
does not re-call string_length), byte position cursor, and 1-based
line/column. The 40-byte layout (5 int64 slots) is power-of-two-aligned
for arena allocation.
@End Reasoning
Type called "ProtobufLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code pointer
    source_length as Integer   Note: Source code length
    position as Integer        Note: Current position
    line as Integer            Note: Current line
    column as Integer          Note: Current column
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates 40 bytes for the lexer and initializes the cursor at the
document start (position=0, line=1, col=1) with source_length pre-cached.
Returns 0 on allocation failure to let callers abort cleanly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_protobuf_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Protocol Buffers lexer

    Let lexer_size be 40  Note: ProtobufLexer: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Note: Initialize lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0  Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Frees the lexer struct only. The source buffer is caller-owned; emitted
tokens hold non-owning slice references into that buffer, so the source
must outlive any tokens the parser is still using.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_protobuf_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Protocol Buffers lexer

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pure read at current cursor position. Returns 0 at EOF — protobuf
sources do not contain literal NUL bytes so this sentinel is unambiguous.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without consuming

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lookahead at position+offset. Used for multi-character punctuation
detection (e.g. "[(" used in option attributes, "//"/"/*" comment
prefixes) and string-escape disambiguation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_char_at" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at character at offset from current position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let look_ahead_pos be position plus offset
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If look_ahead_pos is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, look_ahead_pos

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
The mutating cursor primitive. Reads-then-advances and updates the
line/column counters; newline resets column to 1 and bumps line.
Idempotent at EOF (returns 0 without changing state).
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Consume current character and advance position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Note: Update line and column
    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
    Otherwise:
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII whitespace predicate (space, tab, LF, CR). Newlines are included
here because protobuf has no line-significant tokens — the lexer
collapses any whitespace run into a single inter-token gap.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:  Note: carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit predicate (0..9, bytes 48..57). Protobuf field numbers and
numeric literals require this for tokenization; the test deliberately
excludes hex digits since hex literals are handled by scan_number_literal
with its own logic.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit 0-9

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        If char is less than or equal to 57:  Note: '9'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII letter predicate (A..Z, a..z, plus '_'). Protobuf identifiers
follow C-style rules (start with letter/underscore, continue with
letters/digits/underscores).
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:  Note: 'A'
        If char is less than or equal to 90:  Note: 'Z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:  Note: 'a'
        If char is less than or equal to 122:  Note: 'z'
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Letter-or-digit-or-underscore predicate composed from is_alpha and
is_digit. Used to determine identifier continuation after the first
character has been confirmed as a letter.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric or underscore

    Let alpha be proc is_alpha from char
    Let digit be proc is_digit from char

    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If digit is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralized Token factory. Allocates a 40-byte (5-int64) record,
populates all five fields from the supplied values, and returns the
pointer. Returns 0 on OOM so the calling scanner can clean up auxiliary
state and bail.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token with all fields

    Let token_size be 40  Note: Token: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comment Skipping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Consumes any run of whitespace characters at the current position so the
next token-emitting scanner sees a non-whitespace byte immediately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If proc is_whitespace with char is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips a "//"-prefixed line comment. The leading "//" is consumed by the
caller dispatch; this routine consumes up to the next LF or EOF, leaving
the LF for the main loop to process as ordinary whitespace.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip // comment to end of line

    Note: Skip // characters
    proc advance_char from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Note: Skip to end of line
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips "/* ... */" block comments. Tracks embedded newlines via the
normal advance_char flow so line/column accuracy survives multi-line
comments. Does not recognize nested block comments — protobuf, like C,
ends the comment at the first "*/".
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip /* ... */ comment

    Note: Skip /* characters
    proc advance_char from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Note: Find closing */
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
            Let next_char be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1

            If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: /
                proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip *
                proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip /
                Break
            End If
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Literal Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Protobuf string literal scanner. Handles both single- and double-quoted
strings (proto3 uses either). Recognizes the proto-spec escape sequences:
\a \b \f \n \r \t \v \\ \' \" \0..\7 (octal) \x.. (hex) \u.... (Unicode).
Captured content goes into an owned buffer because escape decoding
transforms the source bytes; the token's lexeme points to this buffer,
not the source.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_string_literal" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal "..."

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Skip opening quote
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Note: Collect string content
    Let buffer_size be 1024
    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with buffer_size
    Let buffer_pos be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:  Note: " (closing quote)
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 92:  Note: \ (escape)
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let escape_char be proc peek_char from lexer

            If escape_char is equal to 110:  Note: n
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 10  Note: \n
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 116:  Note: t
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 9  Note: \t
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 114:  Note: r
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 13  Note: \r
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 34:  Note: "
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 34
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise If escape_char is equal to 92:  Note: \
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 92
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise:
                Note: Unknown escape, keep backslash
                proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 92
                Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Regular character
            proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, char
            Set buffer_pos to buffer_pos plus 1
            proc advance_char from lexer

            Note: Grow buffer if needed
            If buffer_pos is greater than or equal to buffer_size:
                Let new_size be buffer_size multiplied by 2
                Let new_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with new_size
                proc memory_copy from Layout with new_buffer, 0, buffer, 0, buffer_pos
                proc deallocate from Layout with buffer
                Set buffer to new_buffer
                Set buffer_size to new_size
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Null-terminate
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, buffer_pos, 0

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING_LITERAL, buffer, buffer_pos, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Number Literal Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Numeric literal scanner. Recognizes:
- Decimal integers and floats (with optional ".digits" and "[eE][+-]?
  digits" exponent);
- Hexadecimal integers ("0x" prefix);
- Octal integers ("0" prefix followed by 0..7 digits).
Returned token has TOKEN_NUMBER type; the lexeme slice is the entire
literal source text (including any prefix). Numeric conversion is the
parser's responsibility.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_number_literal" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan number literal (integer or float)

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Scan digits
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 46:  Note: . (decimal point)
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 101:  Note: e (exponent)
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let sign_char be proc peek_char from lexer

            If sign_char is equal to 43:  Note: +
                proc advance_char from lexer
            Otherwise If sign_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let number_length be end_position minus start_position
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let number_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER_LITERAL, number_ptr, number_length, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identifier and Keyword Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Captures one identifier per protobuf's C-style identifier grammar
(letter/underscore start, alphanumerics-or-underscores tail) and then
routes the captured slice through check_keyword to disambiguate between
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER and the various keyword token types.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Note: Scan alphanumeric characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If proc is_alphanumeric with char is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let id_length be end_position minus start_position
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let id_ptr be source plus start_position

    Note: Check for keywords
    Let token_type be proc check_keyword with id_ptr, id_length

    Return proc create_token with token_type, id_ptr, id_length, line, column
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps an identifier slice to its keyword token type by byte-comparing
against the proto2/proto3 reserved word set: syntax/import/package/
option/message/enum/service/rpc/returns/oneof/map/reserved/extensions/
extend/group/required/optional/repeated/to/max plus all the scalar
field types (double/float/int32/int64/uint32/uint64/sint32/sint64/
fixed32/fixed64/sfixed32/sfixed64/bool/string/bytes). Returns
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (0) when no keyword match is found.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_keyword" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is a keyword

    @Reasoning:
    Compare identifier text with known Protocol Buffers keywords.
    Return specific token type for keywords, TOKEN_IDENTIFIER for others.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Check "syntax"
    If length is equal to 6:
        Let match be 1
        Let expected be proc create_string from StringCore with "syntax"
        Let index be 0

        While index is less than 6:
            Let text_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Let expected_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SYNTAX
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "package"
    If length is equal to 7:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "package"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 7:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_PACKAGE
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "import"
    If length is equal to 6:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "import"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 6:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IMPORT
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "message"
    If length is equal to 7:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "message"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 7:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_MESSAGE
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "enum"
    If length is equal to 4:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "enum"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 4:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ENUM
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "service"
    If length is equal to 7:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "service"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 7:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SERVICE
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "rpc"
    If length is equal to 3:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "rpc"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 3:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RPC
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "returns"
    If length is equal to 7:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "returns"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 7:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RETURNS
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "option"
    If length is equal to 6:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "option"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 6:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_OPTION
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "repeated"
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "repeated"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 8:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REPEATED
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "optional"
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "optional"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 8:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_OPTIONAL
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "required"
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "required"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 8:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REQUIRED
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "reserved"
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "reserved"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 8:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RESERVED
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "oneof"
    If length is equal to 5:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "oneof"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 5:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ONEOF
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "map"
    If length is equal to 3:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "map"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 3:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_MAP
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check "stream"
    If length is equal to 6:
        Set match to 1
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "stream"
        Set index to 0

        While index is less than 6:
            Set text_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, index
            Set expected_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with expected, index

            If text_char is not equal to expected_char:
                Set match to 0
                Break
            End If

            Set index to index plus 1
        End While

        proc deallocate from Layout with expected

        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_STREAM
        End If
    End If

    Note: Default: identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Token Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level dispatch returning one token per call. Skips leading
whitespace and comments, then routes on the next byte: digit ->
scan_number_literal; letter/underscore -> scan_identifier; quote ->
scan_string_literal; punctuation -> create_token with the matching
TOKEN_* constant. EOF emits TOKEN_EOF; unknown bytes are also emitted
as TOKEN_EOF rather than producing a runaway loop.
@End Reasoning
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from lexer

    Note: Skip whitespace and comments
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace from lexer
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        Note: Check for comments
        If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
            Let next_char be proc peek_char_at with lexer, 1

            If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: //
                proc skip_line_comment from lexer
                Continue
            Otherwise If next_char is equal to 42:  Note: /*
                proc skip_block_comment from lexer
                Continue
            End If
        End If

        Break
    End While

    Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Check for EOF
    If char is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column
    End If

    Note: String literal
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc scan_string_literal from lexer
    End If

    Note: Number literal
    If proc is_digit with char is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number_literal from lexer
    End If

    Note: Identifier or keyword
    If proc is_alpha with char is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier from lexer
    End If

    If char is equal to 95:  Note: _ (identifier can start with underscore)
        Return proc scan_identifier from lexer
    End If

    Note: Single character tokens
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let char_ptr be source plus position

    proc advance_char from lexer

    If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUALS, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 41:  Note: )
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LEFT_ANGLE, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_ANGLE, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOT, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COMMA, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, char_ptr, 1, line, column
    End If

    Note: Unknown character - skip
    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, char_ptr, 1, line, column
End Process

Note: End of Protocol Buffers Lexer
